EL SALVADOR 🇸🇻 Eat the World NYC review: Sometimes a human being just needs a quick pupusa fix. Luckily the place closest to me is very good at making them, and quite a bit of other Salvadoran dishes. A recent return visit also found the hearty soups to be worth exploring, full of chayote and warmth perfect any time of year. ° The restaurant also has a full line of American breakfasts and sandwiches, which brings in a lot of the surrounding blue collar workers that are not yet ready to make the switch to tasty Salvadoran breakfasts and pupusas like many of the families sitting at the tables. ° Oh, and a quick P.S.A.: Don't eat pupusas with a fork and knife you animal!

First time trying this place due to it being highly recommended via word of mouth...Esp. for the pupusas.  Being the only Asian in the restaurant, I was worried the staff wouldnt understand me and would only speak Spanish. But to my surprise, not an issue!  I observed one waitress serving most of the tables, and two people behind the counter for the hot food selection and the cashier register. There's also a kitchen in the back.  I used to work in this area a few years ago but this place wasn't opened yet, otherwise for the $8.95 lunch special (with soda/bottled water) alone, they would have been very popular at my old job. Anyone in this area knows, there isn't much decent eating besides fast food joints and deli stores.... So this place is a gem! And they accept all major credit cards with a $10 minimum.  I bought two lunch orders and two desserts just to sample the menu. And also tried the highly recommended pupusas with pernil (pulled pork) and cheese in it.  (Which was freshly made on the spot, it came with some spicy Cole slaw like item in a bowl and another bowl of sauce that's tomato based. My companion found it to be savory and a taste of El Salvador, since it's a dish that's within their daily consumption. The lunch orders I got was chicken stew and another chicken dish covered in creamy sauce with mushrooms I think. And the rice came with beans and some veggies. It tasted like a nice home cooked meal, with generous portions that delayed my dinner time lol Personally I found the dine-in portion to be larger than the to-go order, but only by a little. And folks, they make a mean cup of Joe !... The aroma will relax you if you ever get it got on the spot and half and half, and milk was accompanied. They sugar selection was well versed with mutiple options available as well.  The flan I ordered is light and sweet, and the texture is very smooth and easily dissolved, kind of like soft tender tofu.... I liked it. The tres leche wasn't the best I've ever had, but it's not bad and def. Better than some others I've tried through out the years and in different neighborhoods.  The two can drinks I got, I thought was soda but they're juices...With a interested texture, like filtered like water, it's thicker than that, tasted good, just extremely high in sugar...47grams...Like yikes!  lol  The owner Mr.Luis Lopez was very hospitable, he greeted us like he saw old friends, even though we only had one Salvadoran at the table lol The rest of his staff was also very friendly and made our dinning experience very homey.  This is def. A very nice little mom and pop shop kind of restaurant, that covers what you'd get at the local deli as well;..I mean their menu is very versatile lol
